From 0315c84ff5ca499e492b6b60ddc3e51724f00f25 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: operations-jacrentals <operations@jacrentals.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 21:58:10 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] Stop counting rentals that never happened as revenue (J1, J2,
 J3)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Three money rollups had no void filter, so cancelled work never left the
books. Verified against production bytes by an independent refute pass before
any code was written; all three came back CONFIRMED.

unitTotalRevenue summed the rate-card price of EVERY rental a unit was ever
listed on — no status check of any kind. Nothing downstream filtered either:
unitRentalPrice derives price from category + dates only, and
rentalUnits/rentalUnitIds/rentalHasUnit carry no status filter. The app's own
billing path already treats voided units as worth nothing: rentalLineItems
filters !unitVoided, setRentalStatus calls removeUnitInvoiceLine the moment a
unit is voided, and setUnitStatus refuses to void a unit while a payment is
still assigned. So a voided unit provably carries $0, yet it was counted as
earned.

The exposure is not only a deliberate cancel-click: rentalDisplayStatus
derives 'No Show' for any Reserved rental whose start date quietly passed —
routine, unavoidable, and silent.

unitRepairCost had the mirror-image hole: ruCatMoney's expense loop skips
cancelled WOs, unitRepairCost did not, so a category's ROI denominator and
its "Expenses by Category" figure — one tab apart on the same card — used two
different definitions of expense.

Filtered PER UNIT via the existing unitVoided(r, eu) convention rather than
dropping whole rentals, so a mixed rental still counts the units that
actually went out. In ruCatMoney the divisor deliberately stays the full unit
count: a voided unit's slice must DROP OUT of revenue, not be redistributed
onto its siblings (which would leave the category total unchanged).

VERIFIED — controlled A/B through the real shipped path (categoryStats ->
unitTotalRevenue), #local seed, both sides loaded cache-busted, voiding one
unit-entry on rental R-A and calling NO reindex:

  trunk  (0 §void-money markers, ?v=20260719b)   avgRevUnit 1038 -> 1038   drop 0
  fixed  (3 §void-money markers, ?v=20260718j)   avgRevUnit  862 ->  346   drop 516

Trunk ignores the void completely; the fix removes exactly that unit's share.
(Baselines differ because trunk has since moved; the delta is the result.)
Isolated separately, the predicates remove exact amounts: unit revenue
3020 -> 440 = -2580, the unit's own price; repair cost 915 -> 695 = -220, the
work order's own line cost.

METHOD WARNING for the next person: two earlier attempts were WRONG and both
were discarded. (1) Calling reindex() inside the measurement moves the stat
identically on both builds, so it cannot distinguish them. (2) A plain reload
is not enough — index.html is cached too, so the page keeps running the old
app.js?v= token and a code change appears to do nothing. Load with a
cache-busting query on the document before trusting any visual check.

Visible change: Total Revenue on a unit, category ROI / avg revenue per unit,
Revenue-by-Category and dollar-utilisation all come DOWN toward the truth.
Time-utilisation is unchanged and should now agree with dollar-utilisation.

Provenance: an agent modified app.js unprompted with a similar change. That
edit was reverted and NOT reused; its line citations were wrong. This was
re-derived from the functions located by name and independently verified.

Gates: smoke, logic-test, lease-test, lease-deploy-test, promote-test,
deck-test, cachebust-test, gen-rule-usage --check, check-window-catalog,
check-design-md, gen-code-map --check — green. check-cachebust is red pending
the ?v= bump /deploy owns.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
